hardest books for me to read in my life because 
every page I was like, "I don't believe it." I  

892
01:08:42,360 --> 01:08:45,720
kept thinking I was a specialist. I kept turning 
the page going, "I don't like this data that keeps  

893
01:08:45,720 --> 01:08:49,400
showing that generalists are better." And then 
by the end, I realized that I'm a generalist.  

894
01:08:49,400 --> 01:08:54,320
It took me so long to realize, and funny for me 
because I ended up redesigning the compensation  

895
01:08:54,320 --> 01:08:58,520
system for Shopify, even though I'm an engineer.
So I still thought of myself as an engineer  

896
01:08:58,520 --> 01:09:01,560
through and through, even though I work 
on recruiting and HR and all these other  

897
01:09:01,560 --> 01:09:05,760
things. But I think that that's what 
we're trying to tease. And then yes,  

898
01:09:05,760 --> 01:09:10,920
in that first period, we actually have a 
survey that goes over Slack that says, "Hey,  

899
01:09:10,920 --> 01:09:16,320
how happy are you with the person that you hired?" 
And that should, in conversation with the person,  

900
01:09:16,320 --> 01:09:19,600
you should give them the feedback to figure out, 
"Hey, are there things you need to adjust to  

901
01:09:19,600 --> 01:09:24,280
better fit in and make sure the expectations are 
set up?" But then also, together with the person,  

902
01:09:24,280 --> 01:09:28,920
figure out, "Hey, if you're not feeling this, 
let's find you either a different role in the  

903
01:09:28,920 --> 01:09:33,080
company or somewhere else because we want the 
people here to have high impact." But that  

904
01:09:33,080 --> 01:09:36,640
person should have high impact somewhere, could 
be at Shopify, could be in the same role, could  

905
01:09:36,640 --> 01:09:41,520
be in a different role, could be at a different 
company. But that's a good thing for everybody.

906
01:09:41,520 --> 01:09:44,240
And then do you actually do work 
trials with new engineering hires,  

907
01:09:44,240 --> 01:09:46,840
or is that something you aspire to do?

908
01:09:46,840 --> 01:09:50,560
Yeah, I would love to do it. It's hard to do 
with the volume resumes we get, but we do do it  

909
01:09:50,560 --> 01:09:55,320
at scale with the internship program. So like 
2025, we're going to hire a thousand interns,  

910
01:09:56,040 --> 01:09:58,720
and that is going to give me a thousand job  

911
01:09:58,720 --> 01:10:03,640
trials to pick the top X percent of 
those to come to Shopify full time.

912
01:10:03,640 --> 01:10:07,200
So just to double-click on that, so 
you're hiring a thousand interns over  

913
01:10:07,200 --> 01:10:13,040
the course of the year. That's a lot. And 
the idea there is these folks are actually  

914
01:10:13,040 --> 01:10:17,360
useful building useful things, and it's 
an interview process for the internship.

915
01:10:17,360 --> 01:10:21,400
Yeah, I think it's two things. One is 
some people look at an internship program  

916
01:10:21,400 --> 01:10:25,360
as community service. Let's give back to the 
community. Let's hire early talent. And I'm like,  

917
01:10:25,360 --> 01:10:31,120
"Hold on a sec. Are you telling me I could hire 
a thousand people over the year?" And they will  

918
01:10:31,120 --> 01:10:35,960
come to work with an LLM and a brain because 
they're growing up in the age of AI. They will  

919
01:10:35,960 --> 01:10:40,360
be useful to us because they come from a different 
generation and they have, in our case in commerce,  

920
01:10:40,360 --> 01:10:45,600
they have a different experience about shopping 
and AI and bots and chat and voice and all these  

921
01:10:45,600 --> 01:10:50,800
things. They'll be useful to us. We'll 
teach them some stuff as well. And then  

922
01:10:50,800 --> 01:10:55,440
together we can decide if they might end up going 
somewhere else, in which case, we have the Shopify  

923
01:10:55,440 --> 01:10:59,800
imprint on them going to whatever other company, 
which is I think a positive, or they might stay  

924
01:10:59,800 --> 01:11:03,920
at Shopify and be useful over a longer period.
It seems like win, win, win. The other thing  

925
01:11:03,920 --> 01:11:08,480
that was cool is after I did that tweet, a 
bunch of other CTOs messaged me and said,  

926
01:11:08,480 --> 01:11:14,160
"Hey, we're going to hire 1,001 interns to beat 
you guys." And I'm like, "Great." Just from  

927
01:11:14,160 --> 01:11:20,200
that one tweet, if I can get the early talent 
ecosystem restarted here after a really tough  

928
01:11:20,200 --> 01:11:25,240
last few years and layoffs, it's great for 
everybody because now they're realizing that  

929
01:11:25,800 --> 01:11:29,680
they also realize that these people are super 
valuable and they bring together a completely  

930
01:11:29,680 --> 01:11:33,760
different set of skills. And by the way, here's 
a secret in pair programming, interns will always  

931
01:11:33,760 --> 01:11:39,960
be more intense than the full-time. And so that 
also helps the flywheel of intensity go for it.

932
01:11:39,960 --> 01:11:44,360
It all just keeps coming back. Did the 
internship program emerge out of this  

933
01:11:44,360 --> 01:11:48,960
co-op system that Canadian schools have 
and a Waterloo has a big co-op program?

934
01:11:48,960 --> 01:11:56,000
Yeah, I went to Waterloo. And so yeah, hint, 
hint. So I went to Waterloo and I did co-op and  

935
01:11:56,000 --> 01:12:00,040
I did intern programs there. It was amazing. What 
a great experience, because what ends up happening  

936
01:12:00,040 --> 01:12:05,400
is you leave Waterloo with your degree, but also 
with two years of experience because I did six  

937
01:12:05,400 --> 01:12:10,080
four-month work terms, 24 months, and you end 
up walking. I think one of the big parts of it  

938
01:12:10,080 --> 01:12:16,360
is just interview skills because I interviewed for 
10 plus jobs every four months, and I did that six  

939
01:12:16,360 --> 01:12:19,760
times. And so you come out having done lots... You 
have a lot of interview experience, but you also  

940
01:12:19,760 --> 01:12:25,520
have work experience. And so just taking that to 
the next level, Shopify has always had interns.  

941
01:12:25,520 --> 01:12:31,640
And what I felt like we needed to do was, 
again, restart this notion of early talent  

942
01:12:31,640 --> 01:12:36,040
in the ecosystem. I would say one or two 
big differences with our intern program. 

943
01:12:36,040 --> 01:12:42,080
One is we're making them come in three days a week 
versus full remote. And the reason for that is,  

944
01:12:42,080 --> 01:12:44,200
and we're doing it just in three 
offices right now in Montreal,  

945
01:12:44,200 --> 01:12:49,040
Toronto and Ottawa. And the reason for that is 
because we want them to have a cohort because  

946
01:12:49,040 --> 01:12:53,640
early talent is different than you and I who've 
been in the industry. We worked in office, we  

947
01:12:53,640 --> 01:12:58,040
worked out of office. We're more comfortable with 
navigating partnership discussions and talking to  

948
01:12:58,040 --> 01:13:02,200
people in different companies. But these people 
have not. They may have never worked anywhere. 

949
01:13:02,200 --> 01:13:08,080
And so to not have the IRL component would do 
them a disservice. And so we specifically made  

950
01:13:08,080 --> 01:13:11,840
it in those ports and the people are traveling 
by the way, they're moving to Montreal to do the  

951
01:13:11,840 --> 01:13:16,720
internship. It's great. And then if you're 
a mentor or manager for one of the interns,  

952
01:13:16,720 --> 01:13:20,160
you have to at least see them like IRL 
once a month. So we're kind of making  

953
01:13:20,160 --> 01:13:23,800
these experiences. And of course, they'll have a 
cohort of dozens of people that will be with them  

954
01:13:23,800 --> 01:13:27,400
along the way. And so we think that'll just 
make their experience better. And of course,  

955
01:13:27,400 --> 01:13:30,960
nothing like tapping someone on the shoulder and 
be like, "Have you seen this era before?" And so  

956
01:13:30,960 --> 01:13:35,160
it's easier in an early talent situation. And then 
of course over time, if they become full-time,  

957
01:13:35,160 --> 01:13:39,480
they can still come to the office. It's come 
if you want, but they can also go full remote.

958
01:13:39,480 --> 01:13:43,720
That is amazing. For folks that don't know 
anything about these co-op programs briefly,  

959
01:13:43,720 --> 01:13:46,600
it's just basically while you're 
in school, before you graduated,  

960
01:13:46,600 --> 01:13:48,760
during the summer, you go work at a company.

961
01:13:48,760 --> 01:13:48,880
No.

962
01:13:48,880 --> 01:13:49,800
Oh, during the year. Okay.

963
01:13:49,800 --> 01:13:53,440
Yeah, it's during the year. So what happens at 
Waterloo is, what I did was I did eight months of  

964
01:13:53,440 --> 01:13:58,400
school at the beginning. So two terms. My first 
co-op term was summer, but then it was work,  

965
01:13:58,400 --> 01:14:01,960
school, work, school, alternating for 
the whole rest of my time at Waterloo.

966
01:14:01,960 --> 01:14:03,640
It's like semesters alternating.

967
01:14:03,640 --> 01:14:07,720
Exactly. So every four months I did either school 
term or work time. So I was doing work in January  

968
01:14:07,720 --> 01:14:12,040
sometimes and September sometimes. And it was 
super good because again, it also allowed me  

969
01:14:12,040 --> 01:14:15,600
to be super intense at school for four months 
and then go to super intense work experience  

970
01:14:15,600 --> 01:14:20,880
for four months. But yeah, it's a model that... 
I was just at Waterloo this week doing a talk,  

971
01:14:20,880 --> 01:14:27,040
so I love that symbiotic relationship between 
Waterloo and the employers, by the way, not just  

972
01:14:27,040 --> 01:14:32,480
Waterloo. Lots of schools do a summer program, 
UFT and others, lots of schools in the states.

973
01:14:32,480 --> 01:14:37,520
Fun fact. So total tangent, I had a startup 
called Local Mine, started it in Montreal of  

974
01:14:37,520 --> 01:14:42,520
all places. I'm not Canadian, but moved there 
for various reasons. It was awesome. And our  

975
01:14:42,520 --> 01:14:46,640
first hire was actually from the co-op 
program. I don't know if it was Waterloo,  

976
01:14:46,640 --> 01:14:50,760
his name is Nick Adams. And he applied. 
Just he saw our job posting, I think,  

977
01:14:50,760 --> 01:14:55,120
and were like, "What is a co-op?" And 
he came to work and then he went back to  

978
01:14:55,120 --> 01:14:59,000
school, and then we hired him, and then 
he ended up at Airbnb when we got a card.

979
01:14:59,000 --> 01:15:06,960
There you go. So for us, actually, when I did 
my startup Helpful, I had one or two engineers,  

980
01:15:06,960 --> 01:15:14,400
and then I actually literally just hired four 
interns because you hired them in February for  

981
01:15:14,400 --> 01:15:19,000
May. And because I was doing pair programming, I 
had to make sure I had four full times by then.  

982
01:15:19,000 --> 01:15:23,520
So I hired the interns in anticipation of 
having the full times. And I literally had,  

983
01:15:23,520 --> 01:15:27,920
I think I was off by one week, so one intern had 
no pair for a week, but then after that in May,  

984
01:15:27,920 --> 01:15:31,360
I had four full times, four interns, 
and then they paired the whole time.

985
01:15:31,360 --> 01:15:36,520
What a journey. I want to talk about just 
one other topic real quick and then we'll  

986
01:15:36,520 --> 01:15:41,640
wrap this up. And it's around XtremeLabs. So 
there's a bunch of stuff here. It feels like  

987
01:15:41,640 --> 01:15:46,520
it's just like this tech mafia of Canada that 
a lot of incredible people emerged out of,  

988
01:15:46,520 --> 01:15:50,480
and there's a whole bunch of stuff we can 
talk about. One fact I heard while you were  

989
01:15:50,480 --> 01:15:56,240
there is you had a hundred reports, 
direct reports that reported to you.

990
01:15:56,240 --> 01:15:57,560
A 120.

991
01:15:57,560 --> 01:16:01,840
120 direct reports feels like 
a complete nightmare to me.  

992
01:16:01,840 --> 01:16:05,880
Tell me why you decided to do that, if 
you'd recommend that for other people.

993
01:16:05,880 --> 01:16:10,720
Yeah, so what ended up happening there was we 
started off small. It was 10 people. When I got to  

994
01:16:10,720 --> 01:16:15,960
XtremeLabs, I wasn't the founder, but I was very 
early on and I just had everyone report to me. And  

995
01:16:15,960 --> 01:16:20,760
then as we grew, I just kept having those people 
report to me and I was trying to figure out,  

996
01:16:20,760 --> 01:16:26,360
we talked about crafters and crafters paradise, 
this idea of people don't really... Their managers  

997
01:16:26,360 --> 01:16:30,560
are useful, but I was trying to figure out 
could I solve the problems that they needed  

998
01:16:30,560 --> 01:16:35,440
their manager for in other ways? So for example, 
what should I be working on? I was like, "Okay,  

999
01:16:35,440 --> 01:16:41,320
well, we have product backlogs" or "I'm blocked 
on something," or "I need feedback on the product  

1000
01:16:41,320 --> 01:16:45,880
I'm building," or "I'm stuck on this technical 
problem." I tried to figure out ways to not  

1001
01:16:45,880 --> 01:16:50,240
have managers be the answers to those questions.
I'm like, "There should be another answer." And so  

1002
01:16:50,240 --> 01:16:54,000
pair programming really helps you get unblocked 
quickly because you have another person that  

1003
01:16:54,000 --> 01:16:57,960
you can bounce technical ideas off of. Having a 
product backlog can tell you what to work on. We  

1004
01:16:57,960 --> 01:17:02,280
had demos every week, demos internally, and then 
we had demos with the clients every week because  

1005
01:17:02,280 --> 01:17:06,040
we were a contract manufacturing for mobile. That 
gave them feedback on whether they were going in  

1006
01:17:06,040 --> 01:17:10,560
the right direction. We had set working hours, 
which made things super intense in the office.  

1007
01:17:10,560 --> 01:17:15,760
This is again like 2009 to 2013. So all these 
things didn't really need a manager. And what  

1008
01:17:15,760 --> 01:17:20,400
I realized was what the unblocking thing needed a 
manager. I'm blocked on this. Well, I said, okay,  

1009
01:17:20,400 --> 01:17:24,320
if... I had all these directors. I did two things 
famously. One, I had a lot of direct reports,  

1010
01:17:24,320 --> 01:17:28,760
and two, I did not do any scheduled one-on-ones 
because you can't have 120 direct reports and  

1011
01:17:28,760 --> 01:17:31,640
do a scheduled one-on-ones because you're 
never doing anything but one-on-ones. 

1012
01:17:31,640 --> 01:17:35,640
So I said, "I'm going to be around a lot 
because I don't have a lot of one-on-ones.  

1013
01:17:35,640 --> 01:17:40,040
So we can do unscheduled one-on-ones." 
And what that means is if you are blocked,  

1014
01:17:40,040 --> 01:17:43,840
actually there's a famous picture where I had 
this weird cube desk where it was like a circle  

1015
01:17:43,840 --> 01:17:48,080
almost in the middle of the whole floor of 
engineers. And I was always there because I  

1016
01:17:48,080 --> 01:17:52,800
wasn't in a lot of meetings and people that were 
blocked, they could just come up to me. Actually,  

1017
01:17:52,800 --> 01:17:57,040
one cool thing about pair programming IRL is you 
can look across and just see if it's working or  

1018
01:17:57,040 --> 01:18:00,520
not. Because if two people are intensely on 
the computer, you know it's working. If one  

1019
01:18:00,520 --> 01:18:01,715
person is laying back or you're like, "It's 
not working," so you can just walk up to-

1020
01:18:01,715 --> 01:18:03,480
It's working if one person is laying back or 
you're like, it's not working. So you could just  

1021
01:18:03,480 --> 01:18:07,920
walk up to them and be like, "What's happening?" 
But they would come and ask me questions and I  

1022
01:18:07,920 --> 01:18:10,480
can unlock them. Like, hey, we're blocked on 
this. We don't have this API. We need money  

1023
01:18:10,480 --> 01:18:16,720
for this machine, whatever. And so the unscheduled 
one-on-ones ended up being a real clarifying thing  

1024
01:18:16,720 --> 01:18:20,760
for me. Because I did scheduled one-on-ones 
my whole career and I realized after leaving  

1025
01:18:20,760 --> 01:18:24,560
Microsoft for three years, I'm like, where are 
all those one-on-ones useful once a week for three  

1026
01:18:24,560 --> 01:18:28,400
years, right? A hundred and fifty one-on-ones.
So the unscheduled ones were, though. I was like,  

1027
01:18:28,400 --> 01:18:32,760
when I knocked on my manager's door and said, 
"I have this problem, those were important."  

1028
01:18:32,760 --> 01:18:37,200
So that's what I created at Xtreme. And the 120 
directors, it just grew over time. I just didn't  

1029
01:18:37,200 --> 01:18:41,080
think I needed managers. So I was like, let me 
unblock these people on another way. And we came  

1030
01:18:41,080 --> 01:18:47,400
up with other things to systems to unblock them 
that didn't require a manager. And I just also  

1031
01:18:47,400 --> 01:18:51,000
had a good memory. I knew exactly everyone's 
skills and compensation. I knew all that off  

1032
01:18:51,000 --> 01:18:56,800
the top of my head, so that helps.
The thing that I broke was actually,  

1033
01:18:56,800 --> 01:19:02,480
this is Chamath. He came in and became our 
biggest investors. He's obviously is a smart guy,  

1034
01:19:02,480 --> 01:19:05,320
but he said the right thing, which is not, 
this can never work, because then I would  

1035
01:19:05,320 --> 01:19:09,640
go into defense mode and explain to him why it 
would work. He just said to me, I'm not going  

1036
01:19:09,640 --> 01:19:14,040
to debate with you whether this works or not, 
but will it work at 400 people? And I said,  

1037
01:19:14,040 --> 01:19:19,000
probably not. He said, okay, so let's change it.
And so we did then ended up putting a little bit  

1038
01:19:19,000 --> 01:19:25,240
more of a structure, but I made a few people 
directors and I forced them to have 40 direct  

1039
01:19:25,240 --> 01:19:30,400
reports each. I said, we're just going to make 
it still pretty flat. And then that did end up  

1040
01:19:30,400 --> 01:19:36,200
working, because it still allowed them to use 
the system to unblock people versus having to  

1041
01:19:36,200 --> 01:19:41,480
do a one-on-one every week, or having 
to talk about things that potentially a  

1042
01:19:41,480 --> 01:19:44,960
system could unblock. And so I tried to 
figure out ways to systematize things.

1043
01:19:44,960 --> 01:19:49,440
I love it. Just another example of doing 
things differently, not necessarily just,  

1044
01:19:49,440 --> 01:19:51,720
here's how it's done and I'm going 
to do it that way and experimenting  

1045
01:19:51,720 --> 01:19:54,240
with it. Even if you knew, okay, 
maybe long term this isn't the way  

1046
01:19:54,240 --> 01:19:58,600
it's going to operate. I imagine at 
Shopify you don't have 120 reports.

1047
01:19:58,600 --> 01:20:04,880
No, we have fourteen or something. We do have 
these guardrails where I think we say, Hey,  

1048
01:20:04,880 --> 01:20:08,640
in engineering you should have between eight 
and 20. There are definitely people who have  

1049
01:20:08,640 --> 01:20:13,120
more and people who have less. But we do try 
to keep things as flat as possible, because  

1050
01:20:13,120 --> 01:20:17,720
we do believe that it doesn't make sense to have 
three people reporting to and then to somebody,  

1051
01:20:17,720 --> 01:20:22,320
and then they only have three people. You just 
make a very deep hierarchy. We actually do see,  

1052
01:20:22,320 --> 01:20:29,440
by the way, the farther you are from Toby, we can 
see things in the survey results. The alignment  

1053
01:20:29,440 --> 01:20:33,600
gets out of whack, and so you do actually see 
that you want to be closer, you want to have a  

1054
01:20:33,600 --> 01:20:39,800
flatter org in general, and that can be achieved 
by just having more direct reports per level.

1055
01:20:39,800 --> 01:20:44,880
Makes sense. Okay, final question before we get 
to our very exciting lightning round. We have  

1056
01:20:44,880 --> 01:20:51,720
this recurring segments that I call Fail Corner 
where generally people come on these podcasts,  

1057
01:20:51,720 --> 01:20:54,120
they share all their successes. 
Here's all the things that I've done,  

1058
01:20:54,120 --> 01:20:57,320
right. Here's all the big wins. 
And everyone feels like, oh man,  

1059
01:20:57,320 --> 01:21:02,120
I wish I was always successful people. When 
in reality, everyone that comes on has failed  

1060
01:21:02,120 --> 01:21:06,400
many times. Is there a story of a failure in 
your career that you could share that helps  

1061
01:21:06,400 --> 01:21:10,720
people see that even folks like you fail, and 
maybe what you learned from that experience?

1062
01:21:10,720 --> 01:21:14,600
I have a few. I'll say one thing by the way, 
because I think I read this in Tim Ferriss's  

1063
01:21:14,600 --> 01:21:18,080
book or in the podcast where he said, create a 
failure resume and write everything down. And  

1064
01:21:18,080 --> 01:21:21,800
I would not recommend doing this because I did 
this and I got super... I'm like a high energy  

1065
01:21:21,800 --> 01:21:26,440
happy guy. I wrote down, I have a note on my 
phone called Failure Resume, and I wrote down  

1066
01:21:26,440 --> 01:21:30,560
all the times I failed and it is depressing. 
So I would not encourage people to do that,  

1067
01:21:30,560 --> 01:21:34,920
but I'm happy to tell you about a few instances.
So well, one is actually I've been laid off  

1068
01:21:34,920 --> 01:21:40,320
twice and people would not expect like, oh, 
I'm doing this thing and I've been laid off  

